  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines introduced\n- Initial focus on financial reporting and suspicious transaction monitoring\n\n2. Major Milestones\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Basel Committee recommendations in 1990s\n- Patriot Act (2001) after 9/11, expanding regulatory oversight\n- Enhanced international cooperation and standardized reporting requirements\n\n3. Key Legislative Improvements\n- Enhanced customer due diligence procedures\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Mandatory suspicious activity reporting\n- increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Advanced anti-money laundering (AML) software\n- Machine learning and AI-powered detection systems\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- More comprehensive global regulatory frameworks\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter sanctions for non-compliant institutions\n- Continuous updating of regulations to address emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legislation has progressively become more sophisticated and comprehensive.",
